'''Blair Timmothy Longley''' (born September 25, 1950) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[politician]] and [[activist]].<ref>[http://www.marijuanaparty.ca/article.php3?id_article=161 Bio from the Marijuana Party website]</ref>

Born in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], Longley attended the founding meeting of the [[Green Party of Canada]] in 1983 and went on to be an active member of the [[Rhinoceros Party]] of which he was official agent from 1985 to 1987.

He joined the [[Marijuana Party (Canada)|Marijuana Party]] shortly after its founding and he became the leader of the Marijuana Party in 2005, following the resignation of [[Marc-Boris St-Maurice]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/canadavotes2006/leadersparties/leaders/bio_otherleaders.html#mbsm|title=Leaders and Parties -Blair Longley Marijuana Party|publisher=[[CBC.ca]]|accessdate=29 August 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160330103133/http://www.cbc.ca/canadavotes2006/leadersparties/leaders/bio_otherleaders.html|archive-date=30 March 2016|dead-url=yes}}</ref>

He has been a candidate for the [[House of Commons of Canada]] on three occasions, each time with a different party label.  He ran for the Green Party in the [[Canadian federal election, 1984|1984 election]] in the [[Riding (division)|riding]] of [[Burnaby (electoral district)|Burnaby]] placing a distant fourth of four candidates with 364 of 58,991 votes.  In [[Canadian federal election, 1988|1988]] he ran against [[Leader of the Opposition (Canada)|opposition leader]] [[John Napier Turner|John Turner]], with no party affiliation, and placed ninth of twelve candidates with 52 of 54,654 votes.

Longley ran for the [[Bloc pot]] in the [[Quebec general election, 2003|2003 Quebec provincial election]]. He later ran for the Marijuana Party in the riding of [[North Okanagan—Shuswap]] in [[Canadian federal election, 2004|2004]] and placed fifth of eight candidates with 492 of 51,765 votes, then in [[Canadian federal election, 2008|2008]] in the riding of [[Hochelaga (electoral district)|Hochelaga]], Quebec, placing eighth of nine with 183 of 45,683 votes.

