{{Use British English|date=November 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}} {{Infobox MP |honorific-prefix = |name = Maria Fyfe |honorific-suffix = |image = |caption = |constituency_MP = [[Glasgow Maryhill (UK Parliament constituency)|Glasgow Maryhill]] |parliament = |majority = 64.9% (1997)<ref>[http://www.alba.org.uk/nextwe/g06.html alba.org.uk: Glasgow Maryhill] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606073340/http://www.alba.org.uk/nextwe/g06.html |date=6 June 2011 }}</ref> |term_start = [[United Kingdom general election, 1987|11 June 1987]] |term_end = [[United Kingdom general election, 2001|7 June 2001]] |predecessor = [[James Craigen (politician)|James Craigen]] |successor = [[Ann McKechin]] |birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1938|11|25}} |birth_place = |death_date = |death_place = |restingplace = |restingplacecoordinates = |birthname = Maria O'Neill |nationality = |party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] |spouse = James Joseph Fyfe (deceased) |relations = |children = |residence = |alma_mater = [[University of Strathclyde|Strathclyde]] |occupation = |profession = |religion = }}
'''Maria Fyfe''' (born 25 November 1938) is a politician in the [[United Kingdom]] and former [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Glasgow Maryhill (UK Parliament constituency)|Glasgow Maryhill]].
==Early life== Born '''Maria O'Neill''', the daughter of James O’Neill and Margaret Lacey, she became a member of the Labour Party in 1960. She returned to education as a mature student, studying Economic History at the [[University of Strathclyde]] and graduatied in 1975. She worked as a senior lecturer in the Trade Union Studies Unit at [[Central College (Glasgow)|Glasgow Central College of Commerce]] from 1978 to 1987. In 1980, she was elected to [[Glasgow District Council]], serving as Vice-Convener of the Finance Committee from then until 1984, when she became Convener of the Personnel Committee. She remained in this position until 1987, when she was elected to Parliament.
==Parliamentary career== At the [[United Kingdom general election, 1987|1987 general election]], Fyfe was returned to [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] as [[Glasgow Maryhill (UK Parliament constituency)|Member for Glasgow Maryhill]], a position she occupied until the [[United Kingdom general election, 2001|2001 general election]]. She served as [[Minister for Women and Equality|Deputy Shadow Minister for Women]] from 1988 to 1991, Convener of the Scottish Group of Labour MPs from 1991 to 1992, and [[Frontbencher|front bench]] spokesperson for [[Scottish Office|Scotland]] from 1992 to 1995. She chaired concurrently the Labour Party Departmental Committee on International Development and the Labour Group in the UK Delegation to the Council of Europe, both from 1997 to 2001. She did not stand for reelection at the [[United Kingdom general election, 2001|2001 General Election]] and was succeeded by [[Ann McKechin]]. Fyfe was awarded an [[Honorary degree|honorary]] D.Univ. by the [[University of Glasgow]] in 2002.<ref>[http://www.gla.ac.uk/news/archive/2002/june/headline_29767_en.html University of Glasgow :: University news :: June 2002]</ref>
She was quoted as saying: "I am proudest of having been involved in the 50-50 campaign to ensure that the [[Scottish Parliament]] started life with an almost equal representation of women, up there with the [[Scandinavia]]n countries".<ref>[http://politics.guardian.co.uk/person/0,,-1848,00.html Fyfe, Maria | Aristotle | guardian.co.uk Politics]</ref>
==Personal life== The then Maria O'Neill married James Joseph Fyfe in 1964; the couple had two sons. Her husband is deceased.
She was interviewed in 2012 as part of [[The History of Parliament]]'s oral history project.<ref name="Life story interview with Maria Fyfe (1938-), former Labour Member of Parliament">{{cite web|title=Maria Fyfe interviewed by Dean White|url=http://sounds.bl.uk/Oral-history/The-History-of-Parliament-Oral-History-Project/021M-C1503X0032XX-0001V0|publisher=[[British Library Sound Archive]]|accessdate=26 January 2018}}</ref>
