{{Infobox military person |name=Pai Tzu-li |birth_date= |death_date=1937 |birth_place=[[Gansu]] |death_place=[[Xinjiang]] |image= |caption=Pai Tzu-li |nickname= |allegiance=[[File:Flag of the Republic of China.svg|20px|Flag of the Republic of China]] [[Republic of China (1912–1949)|Republic of China]] |serviceyears=1929-1937 |rank= [[General officer|general]] |commands=General in the [[36th Division (National Revolutionary Army)]] |unit= [[36th Division (National Revolutionary Army)]] |battles=[[Kumul Rebellion]], [[Xinjiang War (1937)]] |laterwork= }} {{Chinese name|[[Bai (surname)|Bai]]}}
'''Pai Tzu-li''' ({{zh|p=Bai Zili}}) was a [[Hui people|Chinese Muslim]] general of the [[36th Division (National Revolutionary Army)]], who served under Generals [[Ma Zhongying]] and [[Ma Hushan]]. He was the secretary to Ma Zhongying, and his age was estimated to be about 40.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IAs9AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA144&dq=pai+tzu-li#v=snippet&q=pai%20tzu-li%20Chief-of-staff%20secretary&f=false|title=Warlords and Muslims in Chinese Central Asia: a political history of Republican Sinkiang 1911-1949|author=Andrew D. W. Forbes|year=1986|publisher=CUP Archive|location=Cambridge, England|isbn=0-521-25514-7|page=309|accessdate=2010-06-28}}</ref> He was then [[Chief of Staff]] to General [[Ma Hushan]], and persuaded him to attack [[Kashgar]] in 1937.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IAs9AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA144&dq=pai+tzu-li#v=snippet&q=pai%20tzu-li%20Chief-of-staff%20karghalik&f=false|title=Warlords and Muslims in Chinese Central Asia: a political history of Republican Sinkiang 1911-1949|author=Andrew D. W. Forbes|year=1986|publisher=CUP Archive|location=Cambridge, England|isbn=0-521-25514-7|page=142|accessdate=2010-06-28}}</ref>
On September 1, 1937, Pai withdrew to [[Kargilik Town|Karghalik]] at the head of the Tungan 1st brigade. On the 7th of September, Pai, along with Ma Ju-lung and [[Ma Hushan]] deserted their men and fled across the mountains to India.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IAs9AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA144&dq=pai+tzu-li#v=snippet&q=pai%20tzu-li%201st%20brigade%20karghalik%20india%20officers&f=false|title=Warlords and Muslims in Chinese Central Asia: a political history of Republican Sinkiang 1911-1949|author=Andrew D. W. Forbes|year=1986|publisher=CUP Archive|location=Cambridge, England|isbn=0-521-25514-7|page=144|accessdate=2010-06-28}}</ref>
Pai was said to have been shot on the road by Ma Hushan, and did not reach India.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IAs9AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA144&dq=pai+tzu-li#v=snippet&q=pai%20tzu-li%20shot%20on%20the%20road&f=false|title=Warlords and Muslims in Chinese Central Asia: a political history of Republican Sinkiang 1911-1949|author=Andrew D. W. Forbes|year=1986|publisher=CUP Archive|location=Cambridge, England|isbn=0-521-25514-7|page=310|accessdate=2010-06-28}}</ref>
