{{Chinese name|[[Wang (surname)|Wang]]}} '''Wang Jinghong''' ({{zh|c=王景弘|p=Wáng Jǐnghóng|w=Wang Ching-hung}}; died {{circa}} 1434) was a [[Ming dynasty]] Chinese mariner, [[exploration|explorer]], [[diplomat]] and [[fleet admiral]], who was deputy to [[Zheng He]] on his [[treasure voyages]] to Southeast Asia, South Asia, and East Africa, from 1405 to 1433. He led an eighth voyage to Sumatra but is said to have died in a shipwreck on the way.<ref>Tsai, Shih-Shan Henry ''Eunuchs in the Ming Dynasty (SUNY Series in Chinese Local Studies)'' State University of New York Press (13 Nov 1995) {{ISBN|978-0-7914-2687-6}} p.151</ref><ref>Fan, Dainian; Robert Sonne Cohen ''Chinese studies in the history and philosophy of science and technology'' Springer (30 Sep 1996){{ISBN|978-0792334637}} p.313</ref> He was buried at [[Semarang]] in [[Java]] aged 78.<ref>Suryadinata, Leo ''Admiral Zheng He and Southeast Asia'' Institute of Southeast Asian Studies (15 Mar 2006) {{ISBN|978-981-230-329-5}} p.108</ref>
